text: In the pic, he's sitting right inside the garage door waiting for my mom to get home. 🥺 He's been gone for over 3 years now.

I was fortunate to be able to stay with him for a little while shortly before they had to put him down. He was nearly blind and was stressing to get unsteady on his old legs. Seeing this picture today reminded me of how I still miss him anytime I visit my mom.

This was my mom and stepdad's dog, Sarge. They had him from a puppy. He was pretty huge for a Lab. So sweet and loving with a big booming voice. He'd come over and put that huge head in my lap to get his ears scratched. https://t.co/ENeA0Yw1I8

Addendum. This all happened in late 2013/early 2014. Shortly before I moved to PR in May 2014.

I guess what I will say is this: at the time, my access to affordable health care was sketchy at best, and aside from obtaining a diagnosis, being able to routinely afford medication was by far not guaranteed.

So I didn't start this story to say it, but, #MedicareForAll 
11/11

Telling the story is nice. But telling the story and saying "here it is, after all of these years," would be a lot better. But I can't do that.

I have no idea what compelled me to tell this story, but I thought about missing that and felt the need to tell it.
10/11

they had dropped the title "Five Against One" but before the name "Vs." had been decided on. This was the eponymous version w/ no album title. Just Pearl Jam. AND it had the smaller card that hung above it with the release date - my birthday - on it!
9/11

the promotional cardboard album cover for Pearl Jam's second album, which came out on my birthday, Oct 19th in 1994. I was working at Camelot Music and they gave it to me when it finally came down. The coolest part? This artwork had been prepared during the brief period when
8/11

before I got everything out of it. I'm pretty sure there was an acoustic guitar. 

The thing I miss leaving behind the most though was my giant cardboard envelope, full of my posters and other memorabilia.

The thing I lament losing perhaps the most of this collection is
7/11

So, of course, since I didn't have a car at this point, (It'd been a hell of a decade, really) I took my time getting stuff out of this storage unit. And also, of-fucking-course, because it was me, I eventually wasn't able to keep up the payment on the unit 
6/11

Oh, AND, for the stuff that *wasn't* in the dingy, unfinished, basement, I got a storage unit. If I remember correctly, I partly did this because there was a non-trivial gap of time (weeks, I think) between my move-out date and the move-in date at my new apartment.
5/11

If I hadn't been so buried in depression and anxiety, I would've at least done a half-assed job of getting the most important things, and fuck the rest.

But I, apparently, said fuck it all.
4/11

This isn't a story about discovering that you don't need as much as you think. That lesson came later and isn't relevant to this story.

This is the story of how sometimes your mental health fucks you. Ticket stubs collections. Yearbooks. Picture albums. Gone.
3/11

basement. I was told in advance that a junk removal company was scheduled to come and clear out the basement. 

Which means I had the opportunity to take the time - and a flashlight - down those old wooden steps, and find anything that I wanted to keep.

I did nothing.
2/11

So, when I moved out of the house I had been in for 9 years, I was in a pretty dark place, mental health-wise. I remember that all the boxes of stuff that I had been lugging around every time I moved from place to place over the years, was down in this very dingy, unfinished 1/11
